response:
Let $E$ and $F$ be the midpoints of $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{AD}$, respectively.  Then $O$ is the intersection of $\overline{EF}$ and $\overline{AC}$, and $O$ is the center of the rectangle $EFGH$ shown below.

[asy]
size(200);
pair A,B,C,D,E,F,G,H,O;
A=(-250,100); B=(250,100); C=(250,-100); D=(-250,-100); E=(-125,100); F=(-250,50); G=(-125,-100); H=(50,-100); O=(0,0);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(O--E,red);
draw(O--F,red);
label("$A$",A,NW);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$D$",D,SW);
label("$E$",E,N);
label("$F$",F,W);
label("$G$",G,S);
label("$H$",H,E);
label("$O$",O,NE);
[/asy]

Let $P$ be a point in the interior of rectangle $EFGH$ such that $OP < PE$ and $OP < PF$.  Then $OP < PF$ implies that $P$ is closer to $F$ than to $A$ or $D$.  Similarly, $OP < PE$ implies that $P$ is closer to $E$ than to $A$ or $B$.  Therefore, $P$ is closer to $O$ than to any of the four vertices of rectangle $ABCD$.

Conversely, if $P$ is closer to $O$ than to any of the four vertices of rectangle $ABCD$, then $P$ is closer to $E$ than to $A$ or $B$, and $P$ is closer to $F$ than to $A$ or $D$.  Therefore, $P$ is in the interior of rectangle $EFGH$.

Thus, the probability that a randomly chosen point in the interior of rectangle $ABCD$ is closer to $O$ than to any of the four vertices is the ratio of the area of rectangle $EFGH$ to the area of rectangle $ABCD$.  Since $AB/AD=k$, the ratio of the areas is $EF/AD = (AD/2)/AD = \boxed{\frac{1}{2}}$.

